Assistant: <think> Find the area (\( A \)) of the triangle using Heron's formula. Then, use the area to find the lengths of the altitudes. Identify the longest two altitudes and sum them. </think>

\begin{align*}
s & = \frac{\text{sum of sides}}{2} \\
& = \frac{20 + 15 + 13}{2} \\
& = \frac{48}{2} \\
& = 24
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
A_{\triangle} & = \sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)} \\
& = \sqrt{24(24-20)(24-15)(24-13)} \\
& = \sqrt{24 \cdot 4 \cdot 9 \cdot 11} \\
& = \sqrt{9504}
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
x & = \frac{2(13)}{A} \\
& = \frac{26}{\sqrt{9504}}
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
y & = \frac{2(20)}{A} \\
& = \frac{40}{\sqrt{9504}}
\end{align*}

The sum of the two longest altitudes is:

\begin{align*}
x + y & = \frac{26}{\sqrt{9504}} + \frac{40}{\sqrt{9504}} \\
& = \frac{66}{\sqrt{9504}} \\
& = \frac{66}{97.4854} \\
& \approx 0.6777
\end{align*}

